inds of shapes that Fatou and Julia had studied. The images encoded information about when a starting point, when iterated, would escape to infinity, and when it would become trapped in some other pattern. Fatou and Julia’s drawings from 60 years earlier had looked like clusters of circles and triangles — but the computer-generated images that Mandelbrot made looked like dragons and butterflies, rabbits and cathedrals and heads of cauliflower, sometimes even disconnected clouds of dust. By then, Mandelbrot had already coined the word “fractal” for shapes that looked similar at different scales; the word evoked the notion of a new kind of geometry — something fragmented, fractional or broken.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>The images appearing on his computer screen — today known as Julia sets — were some of the most beautiful and complicated examples of fractals that Mandelbrot had ever seen.\u003c/p>\n","fadein":null,"__typename":"ACFContent"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14":{"hide_this_component":null,"acf_fc_layout":"image_component","layout":"medium","regular_caption_right":true,"settings":"","attribution":"\u003cp>Merrill Sherman/\u003cem>Quanta Magazine\u003c/em>\u003c/p>\n","caption":"","mobile_comp_caption":"","mobile_comp_attribution":"","sets":[{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0","typename":"ImageSet"}],"__typename":"ACFImageComponent"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0":{"settings":"","image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0.image","typename":"Image"},"mobile_image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0.mobile_image","typename":"Image"},"mobile_side_margins":true,"mobile_width_constraint":null,"mobile_caption":"","mobile_attribution":"\u003cp>Merrill Sherman/\u003cem>Quanta Magazine\u003c/em>\u003c/p>\n","zoom_image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0.zoom_image","typename":"Image"},"zoom_caption":"","zoom_attribution":"","mobile_zoom_image":null,"mobile_zoom_caption":null,"mobile_zoom_attribution":null,"external_link":"","__typename":"ImageSet"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0.image":{"alt":"","caption":"","url":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_desktop-v4.gif","width":1300,"height":1860,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0.image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0.image.sizes":{"thumbnail":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_desktop-v4-363x520.gif","square_small":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_desktop-v4-160x160.gif","square_large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_desktop-v4-520x520.gif","medium":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_desktop-v4-1202x1720.gif","medium_large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_desktop-v4-768x1099.gif","large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_desktop-v4.gif","__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0.mobile_image":{"alt":"","caption":"","url":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_Mobile-v4.gif","width":560,"height":2552,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0.mobile_image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0.mobile_image.sizes":{"thumbnail":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_Mobile-v4-114x520.gif","square_small":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_Mobile-v4-160x160.gif","square_large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_Mobile-v4-520x520.gif","medium":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_Mobile-v4-377x1720.gif","medium_large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_Mobile-v4.gif","large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/HowtoBuildaJuliaSetbyMerrillSherman_Mobile-v4.gif","__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0.zoom_image":{"alt":null,"caption":null,"url":null,"width":null,"height":null,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0.zoom_image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.14.sets.0.zoom_image.sizes":{"thumbnail":null,"square_small":null,"square_large":null,"medium":null,"medium_large":null,"large":null,"__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.15":{"hide_this_component":null,"acf_fc_layout":"content_area","show_sidebars":false,"content":"\u003cp>Fatou and Julia’s work had focused on the geometry and dynamics of each of these sets (and their corresponding functions) individually. But computers gave Mandelbrot a way to think about an entire family of functions at once. He could encode all of them in the image that would come to bear his name, though it remains a matter of debate whether he was actually the first to discover it.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>The Mandelbrot set deals with the simplest equations that still do something interesting when iterated. These are quadratic functions of the form \u003cem>f\u003c/em>(\u003cem>z\u003c/em>) = \u003cem>z\u003c/em>\u003csup>2\u003c/sup> + \u003cem>c\u003c/em>. Fix a value of \u003cem>c \u003c/em>— it can be any complex number. If you iterate the equation starting with \u003cem>z\u003c/em> = 0 and find that the numbers that you generate remain small (or bounded, as mathematicians say), then \u003cem>c\u003c/em> is in the Mandelbrot set. If, on the other hand, you iterate and find that eventually your numbers start growing toward infinity, then \u003cem>c\u003c/em> is not in the Mandelbrot set.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>It’s straightforward to show that values of \u003cem>c\u003c/em> close to zero are in the set. And it’s similarly straightforward to show that big values of \u003cem>c\u003c/em> aren’t. But complex numbers live up to their name: The set’s boundary is magnificently intricate. There is no obvious reason that changing \u003cem>c\u003c/em> by tiny amounts should cause you to keep crossing the boundary, but as you zoom in on it, endless amounts of detail appear.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>What’s more, the Mandelbrot set acts like a map of Julia sets, as can be seen in the interactive figure below. Choose a value of \u003ci data-stringify-type=\"italic\">c\u003c/i> in the Mandelbrot set. The corresponding Julia set will be connected. But if you leave the Mandelbrot set, then the corresponding Julia set will be disconnected dust.\u003c/p>\n","fadein":null,"__typename":"ACFContent"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.16":{"hide_this_component":null,"acf_fc_layout":"code","layout":"large","code":"\u003cscript src = 'https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/d3/d3-7.4.3.min.js'>\u003c\/script>\r\n\u003cdiv data-viz=\"muji\" style=\"display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; justify-content: center; gap: 36px;\">\r\n  \u003cdiv class='mandelbrot'>\r\n    \u003ccanvas id=\"m_canvas\" >\u003c/canvas>\r\n  \u003c/div> \r\n  \u003cdiv class='julia'>\r\n    \u003ccanvas id=\"j_canvas\"  >\u003c/canvas>\r\n  \u003c/div>\r\n\u003c/div>\r\n\u003cstyle>\r\n  .mandelbrot {\r\n    background-color: white;\r\n    width: 360px;\r\n    height: 360px;\r\n  }\r\n  .julia {\r\n    background-color: white;\r\n    width: 360px;\r\n    height: 360px;\r\n  }\r\n  @media only screen and (min-width: 960px) {\r\n    .mandelbrot {\r\n      width: 440px;\r\n      height: 440px;\r\n    }\r\n    .julia {\r\n      width: 440px;\r\n      height: 440px;\r\n    }\r\n  }\r\n  @media only screen and (min-width: 1080px) {\r\n    .mandelbrot {\r\n      width: 512px;\r\n      height: 512px;\r\n    }\r\n    .julia {\r\n      width: 512px;\r\n      height: 512px;\r\n    }\r\n  }\r\n  @media only screen and (min-width: 1236px) {\r\n    .mandelbrot {\r\n      width: 592px;\r\n      height: 592px;\r\n    }\r\n    .julia {\r\n      width: 592px;\r\n      height: 592px;\r\n    }\r\n  }\r\n\u003c/style>\r\n\u003cscript>\r\n\r\n    function mandelbrot_julia() {\r\n        function mandelbrot(x, y,steps) {\r\n          for (let n = 0, zr = 0, zi = 0; n \u003c steps; ++n) {\r\n            [zr, zi] = [zr * zr - zi * zi + x, 2 * zr * zi + y];\r\n            if (zr * zr + zi * zi > 4) return n;\r\n          }\r\n          return steps\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        function julia(x, y, a, b, steps) {\r\n          for (let n = 0, zr = x, zi = y; n \u003c steps; ++n) {\r\n            [zr, zi] = [zr * zr - zi * zi + a, 2 * zr * zi + b];\r\n            if (zr * zr + zi * zi > 4) return n;\r\n          }\r\n          return steps\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        let resizer;\r\n        function resized(){\r\n            d3.select('#m_canvas').style('visibility', 'visible')\r\n            d3.select('#j_canvas').style('visibility', 'visible')\r\n            muji();\r\n        }\r\n        window.onresize = function() {\r\n            d3.select('#m_canvas').style('visibility', 'hidden')\r\n            d3.select('#j_canvas').style('visibility', 'hidden')\r\n            clearTimeout(resizer);\r\n            resizer = setTimeout(function() {\r\n                resized();\r\n            }, 100);\r\n        };\r\n\r\n        muji();\r\n\r\n        function muji() {\r\n          const m_width = parseInt(d3.select('.mandelbrot').style('width'),10)\r\n          const m_height = parseInt(d3.select('.mandelbrot').style('height'),10)\r\n\r\n          const j_width = parseInt(d3.select('.julia').style('width'),10)\r\n          const j_height = parseInt(d3.select('.julia').style('height'),10)\r\n\r\n          d3.select('#m_canvas').attr('width', m_width).attr('height', m_height)\r\n          d3.select('#j_canvas').attr('width', j_width).attr('height', j_height)\r\n\r\n          const muji_w = m_width\r\n          const muji_h = m_height\r\n\r\n          const m_aMin = -1.85\r\n          const m_aMax = .65\r\n          const m_bMin = -1.25\r\n          const m_bMax = 1.25\r\n\r\n          const m_steps = 48\r\n\r\n          const m_x = d3.scaleLinear().domain([m_aMin,m_aMax]).range([0,muji_w])\r\n          // to accommodate upside down default in canvas\r\n          const m_y = d3.scaleLinear().domain([m_bMin,m_bMax]).range([muji_h,0]) \r\n\r\n\r\n          //const filtered_m_particles = m_particles.filter(d => d.mandelbrot > 8)\r\n\r\n          const mandelbrotCanvas = d3.select('#m_canvas').node();\r\n          const mandelbrotContext = mandelbrotCanvas.getContext('2d');\r\n          \r\n          const juliaCanvas = d3.select('#j_canvas').node();\r\n          const juliaContext = juliaCanvas.getContext('2d');\r\n\r\n          const j_aMin = -1.8\r\n          const j_aMax = 1.8\r\n          const j_bMin = -1.8\r\n          const j_bMax = 1.8\r\n\r\n          const j_steps = 96\r\n\r\n\r\n          const j_x = d3.scaleLinear().domain([j_aMin,j_aMax]).range([0,muji_w])\r\n          const j_y = d3.scaleLinear().domain([j_bMin,j_bMax]).range([muji_h,0])\r\n\r\n          function drawMandelbrot(res) {\r\n            mandelbrotContext.clearRect(0, 0, muji_w, muji_h)\r\n            const m_f = res\r\n            const m_res = 1/(m_f*m_f) // 1/1, 1/4, 1/16, etc\r\n            const m_n = muji_w * muji_h * m_res\r\n          \r\n            const m_particles = new Array(m_n);\r\n            for (let i = 0; i \u003c m_n; ++i) {\r\n              const x = (m_f*i)%muji_w\r\n              const y = m_f*muji_h*Math.floor((m_f*i)/muji_w)/muji_w\r\n              const a = m_x.invert(x)\r\n              const b = m_y.invert(y)\r\n              m_particles[i] = {\r\n                x: x,\r\n                y: y,\r\n                a: a,\r\n                b: b,\r\n                mandelbrot: mandelbrot(a,b,m_steps)\r\n              };\r\n            }\r\n            for (let i = 0; i \u003c m_n; ++i) {\r\n            //for (let i = 0; i \u003c filtered_m_particles.length - 1; ++i) {\r\n              const p = m_particles[i];\r\n              //const p = filtered_m_particles[i];\r\n              if(p.mandelbrot > 8) { // preregistered\r\n                mandelbrotContext.beginPath();\r\n                mandelbrotContext.rect(p.x, p.y, m_f,m_f);      \r\n                mandelbrotContext.fillStyle = d3.scaleSequential(d3.interpolateHcl('transparent', d3.hcl('#005d7a')))(p.mandelbrot/m_steps)\r\n                mandelbrotContext.fill();\r\n              }\r\n            }\r\n            mandelbrotContext.beginPath()\r\n            mandelbrotContext.moveTo(m_x(0),m_y(m_bMin))\r\n            mandelbrotContext.lineTo(m_x(0),m_y(m_bMax))\r\n            mandelbrotContext.moveTo(m_x(m_aMin),m_y(0))\r\n            mandelbrotContext.lineTo(m_x(m_aMax),m_y(0))\r\n            mandelbrotContext.lineWidth = 1;\r\n            mandelbrotContext.strokeStyle = '#82ceef';\r\n            mandelbrotContext.stroke();\r\n            mandelbrotContext.beginPath()\r\n            mandelbrotContext.moveTo(m_x(-1),m_y(m_bMin))\r\n            mandelbrotContext.lineTo(m_x(-1),m_y(m_bMax))\r\n            mandelbrotContext.moveTo(m_x(m_aMin),m_y(-1))\r\n            mandelbrotContext.lineTo(m_x(m_aMax),m_y(-1))\r\n            mandelbrotContext.moveTo(m_x(m_aMin),m_y(1))\r\n            mandelbrotContext.lineTo(m_x(m_aMax),m_y(1))\r\n            mandelbrotContext.lineWidth = .5;\r\n            mandelbrotContext.strokeStyle = '#ccebf9';\r\n            mandelbrotContext.stroke();\r\n          }\r\n\r\n          function drawJulia(j,k,res) {\r\n            juliaContext.clearRect(0, 0, muji_w, muji_h)\r\n            const j_f = res\r\n            const j_res = 1/(j_f*j_f) // 1/1, 1/4, 1/16, etc\r\n            const j_n = muji_w * muji_h * j_res\r\n            \r\n            const j_particles = new Array(j_n);\r\n            for (let i = 0; i \u003c j_n; ++i) {\r\n              const x = (j_f*i)%muji_w\r\n              const y = j_f*muji_h*Math.floor((j_f*i)/muji_w)/muji_w\r\n              const a = j_x.invert(x)\r\n              const b = j_y.invert(y)\r\n              j_particles[i] = {\r\n                x: x,\r\n                y: y,\r\n                a: a,\r\n                b: b,\r\n                julia: 0,\r\n              };\r\n            }\r\n            for (let i = 0; i \u003c j_n; ++i) {\r\n              const p = j_particles[i];\r\n              const juliaValue = julia(p.a,p.b, j, k, j_steps)\r\n              if(juliaValue > 8) {\r\n                juliaContext.beginPath();\r\n                juliaContext.rect(p.x, p.y, res, res);\r\n                juliaContext.fillStyle = d3.scaleSequential(d3.interpolateHcl('transparent', d3.hcl('#A7007D')))((1*juliaValue/(j_steps+1))%1);\r\n                juliaContext.fill();\r\n              }\r\n            }\r\n            // grid\r\n            juliaContext.beginPath()\r\n            juliaContext.moveTo(j_x(0),j_y(j_bMin))\r\n            juliaContext.lineTo(j_x(0),j_y(j_bMax))\r\n            juliaContext.moveTo(j_x(j_aMin),j_y(0))\r\n            juliaContext.lineTo(j_x(j_aMax),j_y(0))\r\n            juliaContext.lineWidth = 1;\r\n            juliaContext.strokeStyle = '#82ceef';\r\n            juliaContext.stroke();\r\n            juliaContext.moveTo(j_x(-1),j_y(j_bMin))\r\n            juliaContext.lineTo(j_x(-1),j_y(j_bMax))\r\n            juliaContext.moveTo(j_x(1),j_y(j_bMin))\r\n            juliaContext.lineTo(j_x(1),j_y(j_bMax))\r\n            juliaContext.moveTo(j_x(j_aMin),j_y(-1))\r\n            juliaContext.lineTo(j_x(j_aMax),j_y(-1))\r\n            juliaContext.moveTo(j_x(j_aMin),j_y(1))\r\n            juliaContext.lineTo(j_x(j_aMax),j_y(1))\r\n            juliaContext.lineWidth = .5;\r\n            juliaContext.strokeStyle = '#ccebf9';\r\n            juliaContext.stroke();\r\n          }\r\n\r\n          function drawDot(x,y) {\r\n            mandelbrotContext.beginPath();\r\n            mandelbrotContext.arc(x,y, 4, 0, 2 * Math.PI);\r\n            mandelbrotContext.fillStyle = '#A7007D';\r\n            mandelbrotContext.fill();\r\n            mandelbrotContext.lineWidth = 2;\r\n            mandelbrotContext.strokeStyle = '#ffffff';\r\n            mandelbrotContext.stroke();\r\n          }\r\n\r\n          let j = -1\r\n          let k = 0\r\n          drawMandelbrot(1);\r\n          drawJulia(j,k,1);\r\n          drawDot(m_x(j), m_y(k));\r\n\r\n\r\n          function dragstarted(event) {\r\n            const e = event.sourceEvent\r\n            j = m_x.invert(e.offsetX)\r\n            k = m_y.invert(e.offsetY)\r\n            drawMandelbrot(2);\r\n            drawDot(e.offsetX, e.offsetY)\r\n            drawJulia(j,k,2);\r\n          }\r\n\r\n          function dragged(event) {\r\n            const e = event.sourceEvent\r\n            j = m_x.invert(e.offsetX)\r\n            k = m_y.invert(e.offsetY)\r\n            drawMandelbrot(2);\r\n            drawDot(e.offsetX, e.offsetY)\r\n            drawJulia(j,k,2);\r\n          }\r\n\r\n          function dragended(event) {\r\n            const e = event.sourceEvent\r\n            j = m_x.invert(e.offsetX)\r\n            k = m_y.invert(e.offsetY)\r\n            drawMandelbrot(1);\r\n            drawDot(e.offsetX, e.offsetY)\r\n            drawJulia(j,k,1);\r\n          }\r\n          \r\n          const drag = d3.drag()\r\n              .on(\"start\", dragstarted)\r\n              .on(\"drag\", dragged)\r\n              .on(\"end\", dragended);\r\n\r\n          d3.select('#m_canvas').call(drag)\r\n          // d3.select('#m_canvas')\r\n          // .on('click', e => {\r\n          //   j = m_x.invert(e.offsetX)\r\n          //   k = m_y.invert(e.offsetY