dium_large":null,"large":null,"__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.32":{"hide_this_component":null,"acf_fc_layout":"content_area","show_sidebars":false,"content":"\u003cp>Yet long before this, mathematicians — just like physicists or biologists or chemists — relied on experimentation to discover and prove new phenomena. They made guesses, discarded hypotheses, looked for patterns by trial and error. They performed computations, made observations, gathered data. They took note of similarities, of certain numbers or sequences arising in unexpected places.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>The giants of 18th- and 19th-century math — Euler, Gauss, Riemann — were all experimentalists who relied on massive amounts of computation, done laboriously by hand. Gauss conjectured the prime number theorem (a crucial formula that describes how the primes are distributed among the integers) a century before it was actually proved. That’s because, as a teenager, he pored over tables of primes and decided to count how many of them there were in blocks of a thousand numbers, all the way up to a million. (No doubt Gauss would have been thankful for today’s computers.) Similarly, Riemann posed his eponymous hypothesis, the biggest open problem in mathematics, only after doing pages of calculations. Those pages weren’t discovered for decades; until then, many mathematicians heralded the Riemann hypothesis as an example of what could be achieved by “pure thought alone.”\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>There’s no such thing. All thinking, mathematical or otherwise, is influenced by the world around us, by the technologies and philosophical movements and aesthetics of our time.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>In this regard, Bourbaki’s philosophy — its requirement for total rigor, and its emphasis on general statements over concrete examples — represented a detour of sorts. Mathematicians’ perspective on Bourbaki is divided. Some claim it gave certain fields a much-needed push toward rigor. Others say it was confining, closed-minded, cutting math off from other sources of inspiration.\u003c/p>\n","fadein":null,"__typename":"ACFContent"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.33":{"hide_this_component":null,"acf_fc_layout":"image_component","layout":"regular","regular_caption_right":false,"settings":"","attribution":"\u003cp>Karen Dias for \u003cem>Quanta Magazine\u003c/em>\u003c/p>\n","caption":"\u003cp>Today, Lyubich is the director of the Institute for Mathematical Sciences at Stony Brook.\u003c/p>\n","mobile_comp_caption":"","mobile_comp_attribution":"","sets":[{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:134276.acf.modules.33.sets.0","typename":"ImageSet"}],"__typename":"ACFImageComponent"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.33.sets.0":{"settings":"","image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:134276.acf.modules.33.sets.0.image","typename":"Image"},"mobile_image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:134276.acf.modules.33.sets.0.mobile_image","typename":"Image"},"mobile_side_margins":false,"mobile_width_constraint":null,"mobile_caption":"","mobile_attribution":"","zoom_image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:134276.acf.modules.33.sets.0.zoom_image","typename":"Image"},"zoom_caption":"","zoom_attribution":"","mobile_zoom_image":null,"mobile_zoom_caption":null,"mobile_zoom_attribution":null,"external_link":"","__typename":"ImageSet"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.33.sets.0.image":{"alt":"","caption":"","url":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/MishaLyubich-byKarenDias-WithLaptop.webp","width":2000,"height":1406,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:134276.acf.modules.33.sets.0.image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:134276.acf.modules.33.sets.0.image.sizes":{"thumbnail":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/MishaLyubich-byKarenDias-WithLaptop-520x366.webp","square_small":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/MishaLyubich-byKarenDias-WithLaptop-160x160.webp","square_large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.